* Speaking of CBS and Trump=E2=80=A6: The former president=E2=80=99s new la=
wsuit over the editing of a 60 Minutes interview with Kamala Harris is ridi=
culous=E2=80=94not least because it flouts the First Amendment and absurdly=
 demands $10 billion for supposedly deceptive trade practices. But there is=
 one critical takeaway for lawmakers. Trump specifically and strategically =
filed the case in a Texas region that ensured the case would be assigned to=
 U.S. District Court Judge Matthew Kacsmaryk, within a circuit that doesn=
=E2=80=99t apply state anti-SLAPP statutes in federal court. This maneuver =
could prolong the litigation, allowing Trump to continue boasting that he=
=E2=80=99s taking on CBS while burdening the system before the case inevita=
bly collapses.

Had Trump filed in California or New York federal court, or even Texas stat=
e court (even though there=E2=80=99s no good jurisdictional reason why it b=
elongs in the Lone Star State at all), CBS could have sought dismissal base=
d on free speech protections and the slim odds of Trump=E2=80=99s success. =
Moreover, CBS could have potentially recouped legal costs from Trump. Inste=
ad, Kacsmaryk has to assume everything Trump alleges is true as he weighs t=
he viability of the claims. This could lead to discovery and possibly, thou=
gh improbably, a trial.

It doesn=E2=80=99t have to be this way. Congress can curb the rising tide o=
f defamation lawsuits aimed at stifling speech. By enacting a robust federa=
l anti-SLAPP law, lawmakers could protect First Amendment rights and reduce=
