ERIQ GARDNER ( https://puck.news/author/eriq-gardner/?utm_campaign=3DWhat+I=
%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F5%2F24%29&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io )

One of the amusing realities of the legal beat is that I=E2=80=99m often lo=
oking backward, sifting through yesterday=E2=80=99s grudges and grievances.=
 But sometimes, I get a glimpse of where the road might actually lead. Case=
 in point: the new 11-year pact giving Amazon the right to stream NBA games=
 starting next season, a deal that=E2=80=99s now ground zero for a legal sl=
ugfest between the league and Warner Bros. Discovery.

WBD is adamant it should be able to match Amazon=E2=80=99s bid and keep the=
 games on TNT. That showdown is headed for a crucial hearing in New York ne=
xt month, where Justice Joel Cohen will weigh the matter. First, however, h=
e=E2=80=99s ordered both sides to justify why parts of the evidence should =
stay sealed. As a result, we=E2=80=99re left with a 35-page contract that=
=E2=80=99s been redacted to the hilt, but still offers a juicy peek into wh=
at could
be a game-changer for NBA commissioner Adam Silver=E2=80=94though not witho=
ut some foreseeable spats.

There are some choice nuggets in the unredacted portions of the contract ( =
https://iapps.courts.state.ny.us/fbem/DocumentDisplayServlet?documentId=3D2=
DnmEjaVwqPjq95ynMhkyw=3D=3D&system=3Dprod&utm_campaign=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing=
%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F5%2F24%29&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io ). Amazon must=
 create new theme music for the games (sorry, John Tesh), NBA logos will ad=
orn Amazon=E2=80=99s never-ending parade of shipping boxes, and for a neat =
$1.8 billion a year, Amazon C.E.O. Andy Jassy is getting primo seats at any=
 game he fancies. Beyond the froth, the contract hints at bigger aspiration=
s. For starters, Amazon must maintain a minimum U.S. subscriber count of 80=
 million (not a big ask, considering
Prime already has about double that). Plus, the NBA maintains audit rights =
on those sub numbers. Oh, and Amazon has promised to promote NBA content, e=
ven forthcoming reality shows, during its Thursday NFL broadcasts=E2=80=94a=
 clause that WBD claims is a poison pill intended to circumvent its ability=
 to match, but might just be a reflection of the NBA=E2=80=99s NFL-sized am=
bitions.

The most interesting element, though, is the way the NBA and Amazon tackle =
new technology. You would think, given how A.I. is rewriting the DNA of bot=
h tech and entertainment, the partners would want a cautious roadmap here. =
Nope. Perhaps they imagine that the bond between Jeff Bezos and Silver will=
 fare better than Bezos=E2=80=99s relationship with Washington Post subscri=
bers. Whatever the rationale, they seem to be laying the groundwork for tom=
orrow=E2=80=99s court battles. Here=E2=80=99s the fine print: There=E2=80=
=99s a =E2=80=9CSuccessor Technology=E2=80=9D clause that concedes that new=
 distribution models
could emerge during the course of the 11-year contract. You think? If they =
do, after year three, Amazon has the option to adopt these innovations for =
NBA broadcasts=E2=80=94with the NBA=E2=80=99s consent, which can=E2=80=99t =
be unreasonably withheld or padded with costs.

So, let=E2=80=99s say that in three years virtual reality, augmented realit=
y, or some other next-gen format becomes the hot new way to watch games. An=
d let=E2=80=99s say Apple, Google, or Meta shows up at Silver=E2=80=99s hou=
se with a truckload of cash to buy those rights. Would the NBA be incentivi=
zed to argue that those rights fall outside of the existing contract with A=
mazon? Or what if Amazon decides to bundle Prime into some yet-unnamed vent=
ure, calling it a =E2=80=9Cnew model=E2=80=9D? How much can the NBA really =
hold the reins or impose limits? In short, just how much room is there for =
the league to =E2=80=9Creasonably=E2=80=9D say no? It feels like the partie=
s settled on weak, ambiguous contractual language and decided this would be=
 a
=E2=80=9Ctomorrow problem.=E2=80=9D To my eyes and those I consulted, these=
 questions are ripe for competing interpretations and could easily be the c=
rux of a future mega-dispute.

And why not? That=E2=80=99s exactly what=E2=80=99s playing out now. The NBA=
 struck a cozy deal with TNT way back when, but somewhere along the way, th=
e parties failed to lock down what would happen when viewers ditched cable =
for streaming. Deal lawyers never seem to learn from history. Next time, ma=
ybe they=E2=80=99ll call in a divorce lawyer to draft the prenup. But I wou=
ldn=E2=80=99t bet on it.

That=E2=80=99s it for today. Go vote! And I=E2=80=99ll see you on Thursday.

Matt

