          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">One of the amusing =
realities of the legal beat is that I=E2=80=99m often looking backward, sif=
ting through yesterday=E2=80=99s grudges and grievances. But sometimes, I g=
et a glimpse of where the road might actually lead. Case in point: the new =
11-year pact giving Amazon the right to stream NBA games starting next seas=
on, a deal that=E2=80=99s now ground zero for a legal slugfest between the =
league and Warner Bros. Discovery. <br/><br/>WBD is adamant it should be ab=
le to match Amazon=E2=80=99s bid and keep the games on TNT. That showdown i=
s headed for a crucial hearing in New York next month, where Justice <b>Joe=
l Cohen</b> will weigh the matter. First, however, he=E2=80=99s ordered bot=
h sides to justify why parts of the evidence should stay sealed. As a resul=
t, we=E2=80=99re left with a 35-page contract that=E2=80=99s been redacted =
to the hilt, but still offers a juicy peek into what could
be a game-changer for NBA commissioner <b>Adam Silver</b>=E2=80=94though no=
t without some foreseeable spats.<br/><br/>There are some choice nuggets in=
 the unredacted portions of <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlb=
WFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dTX3ROSmJGd1ozUnBCaWQ5QU5aaz0iLCJocmVm=
IjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9pYXBwcy5jb3VydHMuc3RhdGUubnkudXMvZmJlbS9Eb2N1bWVudERpc3BsYXl=
TZXJ2bGV0P2RvY3VtZW50SWQ9MkRubUVqYVZ3cVBqcTk1eW5NaGt5dz09XHUwMDI2c3lzdGVtPX=
Byb2RcdTAwMjZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249V2hhdCtJJTI3bStIZWFyaW5nJTJCKy0rU1VCU0NSSUJFU=
lMrJTI4MTElMkY1JTJGMjQlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvIiwiaW50ZXJu=
YWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjoxOTY1OTg3fQ/5c58146eb3d72402=
8a07b42ca04d38f0f3bfd6df1cd84a5385bbb44596332d99" style=3D"color:#d40000;te=
xt-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">the contract</a></u>. Am=
azon must create new theme music for the games (sorry, <b>John Tesh</b>), N=
BA logos will adorn Amazon=E2=80=99s never-ending parade of shipping boxes,=
 and for a neat $1.8 billion a year, Amazon C.E.O. <b>Andy Jassy</b> is get=
ting primo seats at any game he fancies. Beyond the froth, the contract hin=
ts at bigger aspirations. For starters, Amazon must maintain a minimum U.S.=
 subscriber count of 80 million (not a big ask, considering
Prime already has about double that). Plus, the NBA maintains audit rights =
on those sub numbers. Oh, and Amazon has promised to promote NBA content, e=
ven forthcoming reality shows, during its Thursday<i> NFL </i>broadcasts=E2=
=80=94a clause that WBD claims is a poison pill intended to circumvent its =
ability to match, but might just be a reflection of the NBA=E2=80=99s NFL-s=
ized ambitions.<br/><br/>The most interesting element, though, is the way t=
he NBA and Amazon tackle new technology. You would think, given how A.I. is=
 rewriting the DNA of both tech and entertainment, the partners would want =
a cautious roadmap here. Nope. Perhaps they imagine that the bond between <=
b>Jeff Bezos</b> and Silver will fare better than Bezos=E2=80=99s relations=
hip with <i>Washington Post</i> subscribers. Whatever the rationale, they s=
eem to be laying the groundwork for tomorrow=E2=80=99s court battles. Here=
=E2=80=99s the fine print: There=E2=80=99s a =E2=80=9CSuccessor Technology=
=E2=80=9D clause that concedes that new distribution models
could emerge during the course of the 11-year contract. <i>You think?</i> I=
f they do, after year three, Amazon has the option to adopt these innovatio=
ns for NBA broadcasts=E2=80=94with the NBA=E2=80=99s consent, which can=E2=
=80=99t be unreasonably withheld or padded with costs.<br/><br/>So, let=E2=
=80=99s say that in three years virtual reality, augmented reality, or some=
 other next-gen format becomes the hot new way to watch games. And let=E2=
=80=99s say Apple, Google, or Meta shows up at Silver=E2=80=99s house with =
a truckload of cash to buy those rights. Would the NBA be incentivized to a=
rgue that those rights fall outside of the existing contract with Amazon? O=
r what if Amazon decides to bundle Prime into some yet-unnamed venture, cal=
ling it a =E2=80=9Cnew model=E2=80=9D? How much can the NBA really hold the=
 reins or impose limits? In short, just how much room is there for the leag=
ue to =E2=80=9Creasonably=E2=80=9D say no? It feels like the parties settle=
d on weak, ambiguous contractual language and decided this would be a
=E2=80=9Ctomorrow problem.=E2=80=9D To my eyes and those I consulted, these=
 questions are ripe for competing interpretations and could easily be the c=
rux of a future mega-dispute. <br/><br/>And why not? That=E2=80=99s exactly=
 what=E2=80=99s playing out now. The NBA struck a cozy deal with TNT way ba=
ck when, but somewhere along the way, the parties failed to lock down what =
would happen when viewers ditched cable for streaming. Deal lawyers never s=
eem to learn from history. Next time, maybe they=E2=80=99ll call in a divor=
ce lawyer to draft the prenup. But I wouldn=E2=80=99t bet on it.<br/></td>
